entry.title: Throw an exception in putImageData if canvas layers are opened
entry.content:
This API is incompatible with how the 2D canvas is rasterized when

it contains unclosed layers. Because layers can have filters that get

applied on their final content, they can't be presented until they are

closed. Instead, we normally keep the layer content alive after a

flush, so that it can be presented in a later frame when the layer is

finally closed.



putImageData however is supposed to write to the canvas bitmap

wholesale, bypassing all render states. This means that we can't write

to the layer's content because the written pixels would then get

filtered when the layer is closed. We can't write to the main canvas

either because these pixels would later be overwritten by the layer's

result with draw calls that potentially happened before (e.g. in the

sequence `beginLayer(); fillRect(); putImageData(); endLayer();`,

`fillRect()` would write over `putImageData()`.



This behavior is part of the current 2D Canvas Layer spec draft:

Explainer: https://github.com/fserb/canvas2D/blob/master/spec/layers.md

Spec draft: https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9537

entry.title: Codelabs: Add three mojo examples, including frozen associated interfaces
entry.content:
Please see `codelabs/mojo_examples/README.md` for a detailed explanation

of what all this CL includes. In short, this CL adds 3 "codelabs"

examples demonstrating:

1.) Using Mojo Invitations to create an initial cross-process channel

2.) How //base TaskQueue scheduling interacts with Mojo associated

interfaces, for both "pure" Mojo associated interfaces and the

legacy IPC channel-associated interfaces, which have observable

differences



The point of these demos is to show practical examples of Mojo being

used in a multi-process setting *outside* of Chromium code to help de-

mystify how it works and what's going on under the hood when Chromium

launches a new child process that is connected to its parent via Mojo,

and how we register associated interfaces. The examples include 6

binaries that are toy recreations of the "browser" and "renderer"

processes just for demonstration purposes.



One of the main motivations for this CL is to concretely demonstrate

the very under-documented observable difference between:

1. Traditional mojo-associated interface scheduling

2. Legacy IPC channel-associated interface scheduling



If two mutually-associated interfaces are bound to receivers that are

connected to different TaskQueues, even on the same thread, then in

configuration (1) above mojo guarantees the ordering of the messages.

This is not the case for configuration (2) above, however. This makes it

possible for legacy IPC channel-associated to get out of order. This is

a non-trivial behavior difference, and the examples in this CL provide

practical examples illustrating this.

entry.title: Throw an exception in transferToImageBitmap if canvas layers are opened
entry.content:
This API is incompatible with how the 2D canvas is rasterized when

it contains unclosed layers. Because layers can have filters that get

applied on their final content, they can't be presented until they are

closed. Instead, we normally keep the layer content alive after a

flush, so that it can be presented in a later frame when the layer is

finally closed.



OffscreenCanvas.transferToImageBitmap however is supposed to release

the canvas content, leaving the offscreen canvas empty. We cannot

release the recording if layers are incomplete, and if we kept the

layer content alive for later, we would not be leaving the canvas

empty as the spec requires.



This behavior is part of the current 2D Canvas Layer spec draft:

Explainer: https://github.com/fserb/canvas2D/blob/master/spec/layers.md

Spec draft: https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9537

entry.title: webview: Add top level origin to web messages in java
entry.content:
We are exploring the utility of platform specific APIs for WebView.

One issue we are running into is that we can't fully partition data

like Chrome because the web message only contains the source origin

but does not contain the top level origin.



Ideally we'd like to use the storage key for this but it has two

entry.title: documentScan: Add DocumentScanAPIHandler
entry.content:
The existing documentScan.scan function is implemented directly in the

API function class because there was only a single function in the

documentScan API. New functions are going to be added that need to talk

to the same DocumentScan service, so introduce a separate

DocumentScanAPIHandler class and move the existing logic into it.



Because the additional scanning functions are going to have requirements

similar to the chrome.printing API, the new class is modeled closely

after PrintingAPIHandler. It provides more functionality than is needed

for the existing scan function, but will be appropriate once the new API

functions start being added.



The only behavior change in the new version is that MIME types are

checked before fetching the list of available scanners. This means that

passing an invalid MIME type with no scanners attached will now return

"Invalid MIME type" instead of "No scanners available". Scanner names

are not exposed in the API and both checks have to pass before a scan is

started, so the only real effect is to make the invalid MIME case fail

faster.



Bug: b:297435442

Test: tast run documentscanapi.Scan

Test: Sample extension with physical scanners on a Chromebook

and if this will bring results, a follow up CL will stop sending

all other blocking requests.

entry.title: Remove {On/Did}StartLoadingResponseBody()
entry.content:
Currently when MojoURLLoaderClient::OnReceiveResponse() receives the

response, it calls two methods OnReceivedResponse() and

OnStartLoadingResponseBody().



Before this CL:

- MojoURLLoaderClient::OnReceiveResponse()

- ResourceRequestSender::OnReceivedResponse()

- URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedResponse()

- ResourceLoader::DidReceiveResponse()

- ResourceRequestSender::OnStartLoadingResponseBody()

- URLLoader::Context::OnStartLoadingResponseBody()

- ResourceLoader::DidStartLoadingResponseBody()



After this CL:

- MojoURLLoaderClient::OnReceiveResponse()

- ResourceRequestSender::OnReceivedResponse()

- URLLoader::Context::OnReceivedResponse()

- ResourceLoader::DidReceiveResponse()



There is a historical reason that the renderer process received the

response and the body in two IPCs (OnReceiveResponse,

OnStartLoadingResponseBody). But now they have been merged by

https://crrev.com/c/3410912. So we don't need to keep two methods.



Bug: 1379780

entry.title: Skip OnAppUpdate if there is no change for the published apps.
entry.content:
When the AppStorage is enabled, the apps could be published twice by

AppStorage and publishers with the same app info. For example:

1. Read AppStorage, and publish the builtin apps.

2. Builtin apps publisher is created, and publish the builtin apps

again.

Then OnAppUpdate could be called twice as well.



This CL modifies AppRegistryCache, to compare delta and state. If there

is no change, don't call OnAppUpdate.



Set paused as false in AppStorage to keep the consistent implementation

as publishers, as that is the default init value in AppPublisher.



Clean up app_registry_cache_unittest to remove the tests added for the

non mojom work.



BUG=1385932

entry.title: Report full page process list in ReportPageProcessesPolicy
entry.content:
The page process list is sent to the resource manager daemon

(resourced). The page process list is used to estimate the memory usage

of the background and protected processes. Based on the Chrome memory

usage, resourced determines when to release memory from Chrome or VMs or

container. When there are a lot of background processes in Ash Chrome,

resourced avoids killing perceptible apps in VMs or container.



If the last page node event is within the miminum report interval, start

a timer to ensure the page process list is reported after the last page

node event.



Deprecate crosapi ReportBackgroundProcesses.
